PSEUDOCODE
==========

Enable clock for TIM2
Configure TIM2:
    Set Prescaler (PSC) -> scale down 16MHz to 1MHz (1 tick = 1µs)
    Set Auto-Reload Register (ARR) -> count up to desired delay
    Set counting mode -> upcounting
    Enable TIM2

delay_us(n):
    Reset counter to 0
    Set ARR to n
    Clear update event flag (UIF)
    Start timer
    Wait until UIF flag is set (counter hit ARR)
    Stop timer

delay_ms(n):
    Call delay_us(n * 1000)

Main:
    Setup PA5 as output (LED)
    Loop forever:
        Toggle LED
        delay_ms(500)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   =>  Onboard LED (LD4) - Active HIGH

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

RCC (Reset and Clock Control)
|--------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register     | Field          | Description                                                    |
|--------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|
| RCC->APBENR1 | TIM2EN (bit 0) | Enables clock for TIM2. TIM2 sits on APB1 bus, not IOPORT bus. |
|--------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|

TIM2 (General-Purpose Timer)
|-----------|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register  | Field      | Description                                                                                                              |
|-----------|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| TIM2->PSC | bits[15:0] | Prescaler. Timer input clock is divided by (PSC + 1). At 16MHz, PSC=15 gives 1MHz tick.                                  |
| TIM2->ARR | bits[31:0] | Auto-Reload Register. Counter counts up to this value, then triggers update event and resets. TIM2 is 32-bit on STM32G0. |
| TIM2->CNT | bits[31:0] | Current counter value. Write 0 to reset it before starting a timed delay.                                                |
| TIM2->CR1 | bit0 CEN   | Counter Enable. Set to start, clear to stop the timer.                                                                   |
| TIM2->CR1 | bit3 OPM   | One Pulse Mode. Counter stops automatically after one update event. Perfect for delays.                                  |
| TIM2->EGR | bit0 UG    | Update Generation. Writing 1 forces an update event - reloads PSC and ARR immediately into shadow registers.             |
| TIM2->SR  | bit0 UIF   | Update Interrupt Flag. Set by hardware when counter reaches ARR. Must be cleared manually.                               |
|-----------|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY CONCEPTS
============

Shadow Register in STM32 TIM Peripheral

Shadow registers are a double-buffering mechanism used in STM32 timers to ensure
safe, glitch-free updates to timer configuration during operation. When a timer
is running, we might want to change its period, duty cycle, or compare value. If
we write directly to the active register while the timer is counting, we risk:
Inconsistent behavior, Glitches, Timing errors. The value in shadow registers is
transferred to the active registers only on an Update Event (UEV) - typically
when the timer overflows or resets. There are specific bits which enables and
disables the use of shadow registers, but PSC Register always has shadow
registers (always buffered).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* PSC off-by-one,1 Just like SysTick's LOAD, the prescaler divides by PSC + 1,
  not PSC. For a 1MHz tick from 16MHz: PSC = 15, not 16. If the delays are
  consistently ~6% too long, this is why.

* PSC not loading without EGR|=UG, PSC and ARR have shadow registers. The value
  we write doesn't take effect until the next update event. If we skip EGR |=
  (1U << 0) during init, the first delay will use whatever garbage was in the
  shadow register at reset. Always force an update event after setting PSC.

* Not clearing UIF before starting, If a previous delay left UIF set and we
  don't clear it, the while(!(SR & UIF)) exits immediately on the next call,
  giving us a near-zero delay. Clear UIF before enabling the counter, not after.

* delay_ms via loop vs single large ARR, we might be tempted to set ARR = ms *
  1000 directly for millisecond delays. This works for small values but remember
  ARR is loaded into a 32-bit register, the math is fine. However, at 1µs
  resolution, delay_ms(1000) would set ARR = 1,000,000 which is valid. The loop
  approach here keeps delay_micro_sec reusable and clean.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* TIM2 is 32-bit on STM32G0, Unlike many STM32 families where TIM2 is 16-bit, on
  the G0 series TIM2 has a full 32-bit counter and ARR. This means we can count
  up to 0xFFFFFFFF ticks, at 1MHz that's over an hour in a single reload. No
  chaining needed for long delays.

* Shadow registers are a feature, not a bug, PSC and ARR are buffered. Writes to
  them only apply on the next update event. This is intentional, it prevents
  glitches mid-period if we change the reload value while the counter is
  running. In PWM programs , we'll update ARR on the fly and this buffering
  becomes essential.

* OPM vs manual stop, One Pulse Mode (CR1 bit 3) automatically clears CEN when
  the counter reaches ARR. This is cleaner than manually clearing it, but we
  still clear it explicitly for safety. In continuous mode (no OPM), the counter
  wraps and keeps going, which is exactly what PWM Program needs.

* TIM2 vs SysTick for delays, SysTick gives us a free-running 1ms timebase with
  an ISR, great for non-blocking timing patterns. TIM2 used here is a blocking
  one-shot delay with microsecond precision, great when we need tight µs-level
  timing. Both have their place. From now onwards, SysTick handles coarse timing
  and TIM2 is freed up for PWM and input capture.
